feat(kms): openbao-gated secrets manager + LUKS volumes for confidential workloads

Ship the c8s Secrets Manager Proxy (whitepaper §4.3, §5.6.4) as an
attestation-gated broker in front of a vanilla OpenBao/Vault, plus a
c8s-native LUKS volume path so a confidential workload can attach a
persistent encrypted disk without ever handing a passphrase to the host.

`internal/cmds/secretbroker/` — a subset of the Vault HTTP API (health,
cert/login, token/lookup-self, KV v2 read). Every request is
authenticated at TLS: `ratls` (default) verifies the caller's TEE
attestation report against `--measurements`; `ca` verifies the CDS
mesh-issued client cert and identifies the caller by SAN. Both modes
pass the peer identity to a deny-by-default JSON release policy that
maps `(workloadId, measurement) → allowed KV paths`. On `cert/login`
the broker mints a short-TTL token bound to the caller's client cert
(a stolen token cannot be replayed on another cert). The broker
authenticates to the store with its own token / AppRole. Store
attestation is required by default (RA-TLS to OpenBao); `attested=false`
is documented as the trust edge for external stores.

Stock `bao` and `vault` agents work against the broker unchanged — it
IS the Vault HTTP API. Chart wires the release policy in via values,
mounts the broker's credential as a file (kept out of argv), and pins
the broker as a mesh component under kata.

`internal/webhook/secrets.go`, `luks.go` — two annotation families for
confidential workloads:

    confidential.ai/secrets-inject: "true"
    confidential.ai/secret-<name>: <kv-path>[#<field>]
    confidential.ai/luks-<name>: dev=<path>,mount=<mount>,secret=<kv-path>#<field>[,fstype=ext4][,mode=open|format-if-empty]

When set, the webhook injects (after the existing c8s-cert init):

  * c8s-secrets-config — renders the Vault Agent config in-image (in
    the measured c8s binary), never through a ConfigMap.
  * c8s-secrets-agent-init — the unmodified OpenBao/Vault Agent as a
    one-shot: auth via mesh cert → template each secret to
    /vault/secrets/<name> → exit and gate the next init.
  * c8s-secrets-agent — optional renewal sidecar (Renew: true).
  * c8s-luks-open — reads passphrase files the agent templated,
    cryptsetup-formats (if mode=format-if-empty) / opens the
    referenced block device, mkfs on first use, mounts the mapper for
    the app container. Runs privileged as root (block-device ops
    require CAP_DAC_OVERRIDE / mount).

Fail-closed guards land at admission:
  * secrets-inject without a matching --secret-agent-image on the
    operator → 400 (an app that comes up missing its secret files
    should never be admitted).
  * luks-<name> without a matching secret-<name> or without
    secrets-inject: true → 400 (the passphrase must exist as a file
    before luks-open runs, or luks-open would race and crash).
  * secretBroker.peerVerify=ratls under kata.enabled=true → chart
    render fails with kind=broker_ratls_under_kata — see the design
    doc below for the underlying architectural gap.

`internal/cmds/luksopen/` — the runtime driver the webhook injects.
Reads passphrase files from --secrets-dir; for each --volume spec
runs `cryptsetup isLuks` → `luksFormat --batch-mode` (mode=
format-if-empty only) → `luksOpen` → blkid → `mkfs.<fstype>` if the
mapper is empty → mount at --mount-root/<name>. Idempotent on pod
restart: skips volumes whose mount is already present in
/proc/self/mountinfo. Passphrase files with trailing newlines are
handled correctly (cryptsetup takes the whole file including the
newline; we strip it).

`internal/cmds/luks/` — operator-facing management of encrypted
volumes:

    c8s luks create --workload <cw-id> --name <n> --size <qty>
                    [--driver local|pvc|csi] [--fstype ext4]
                    [--defer-format] [--passphrase-entropy 32]
    c8s luks list    --workload <cw-id>
    c8s luks show    --workload <cw-id> --name <n>   # no passphrase disclosure
    c8s luks destroy --workload <cw-id> --name <n> [--force]

Passphrases are 32-byte crypto/rand, hex-encoded, never printed to
stdout (only openbao sees them). KV write happens BEFORE any host
mutation so a failed openbao doesn't leave a formatted disk with an
unknown passphrase; host-mutation failures roll back the KV entry so
a retry starts fresh. The `local` driver is implemented end-to-end
(dd + losetup + luksFormat + mkfs + luksClose, and matching
detach/delete on destroy). `pvc` and `csi` return "not yet
implemented" so the flag surface is stable when they're added.

The CLI emits pod annotations + a volume snippet matching Stage 5's
parser exactly — the intended workflow is
`c8s luks create ... | yaml → kubectl edit / helm / gitops`, never
"apply to a workload" magic.

`internal/issuer/sign.go`, `internal/cmds/cds/attest.go` — every mesh
leaf CDS mints now carries the workload's already-verified TEE report
as OID 1.3.6.1.4.1.59888.1.1 (SNP: raw report; TDX: /verify envelope,
via the existing attestclient.RATLSEvidence helper). Downstream
ratls-mode verifiers (ratls.VerifyCert, `c8s cds verify`) see the
same measurement CDS accepted, without a second attestation round-trip.
Server-supplied evidence takes precedence over any client-supplied
.1.1 in the CSR (the issuer's just-verified evidence is authoritative).

Non-fatal if extraction fails — the mesh cert still issues without
.1.1 so no regression for existing CA-chain-only verifiers.

Two independent E2E paths:

**Hardware-free (`scratchpad/broker-openbao-e2e.sh`)** — spins the
broker as a local process, points it at the deployed openbao via
port-forward, drives cert/login → token → KV read via curl+mTLS.
Returns the expected password. Proves the broker + release policy +
KV brokering + token binding all work as a unit.

**In-cluster on Azure SEV-SNP CVM (`--cvm-mode=aks`, vTPM path)** —
c8s-cert obtains the mesh cert through vTPM attestation; the injected
Vault Agent authenticates to the broker (release policy matches on
the mesh SAN); c8s-luks-open reads the templated passphrase and
cryptsetup-formats /dev/loop0; the app container writes a marker to a
LUKS-mounted /data. Confirms every stage on the golden path.

* 2026-07-09-broker-peer-verify-under-kata.md — records that
  `secretBroker.peerVerify=ratls` under `--kata` is inert (the
  in-guest ratls-mesh sidecar terminates TLS in front of the broker
  with its OWN bootstrap cert, so the broker never sees the peer's
  measurement). Option A step 1 (this branch) fixes the mesh-leaves-
  lack-.1.1 half; step 2 (identity forwarding OR out-of-mesh port)
  is tracked. The chart validation `kind=broker_ratls_under_kata`
  guards until step 2 lands.

* 2026-07-10-openbao-luks.md — the LUKS design: annotation grammar,
  fail-closed guards, threat model (host doesn't see the passphrase
  at any point; the block device is dm-crypt-encrypted so the host
  sees only ciphertext), seam with PR #295 (PR #295's kata-guest
  scratch disk uses per-boot random key + guest never persists;
  ours uses openbao-issued key + persists across reboots — they
  coexist as separate disks with separate threat models), and the
  deferrals (rotation, dm-integrity under dm-crypt, RWX, and the
  PVC controller).

* 2026-07-10-luks-cli.md — the Stage 6 CLI shape, driver interface,
  passphrase entropy defaults, the deliberate "no auto-apply" UX.

* `attestation-api` is built in a sibling repo, so a branch install
  pinned to a c8s CI tag hits 404 on that image. Fix: pin
  `attestationApi.image.tag=main` via `-f` or `--resolve-digests=false`.
* CDH inside the guest sends the baked ghcr-auth.json unconditionally
  and hard-fails 401 if it's stale — not falls back to anonymous. Fix
  is to rebuild kata-guest-base with a fresh READ_PRIVATE_GHCR_TOKEN;
  break-glass is `kata.guestImage.registryAuth=""`.
* Under `--cvm-mode=baremetal` + `--kata` the workload-pod get-cert
  path is not currently functional — mesh interaction detail we could
  not root-cause on the test box. `--cvm-mode=aks` (Azure CVM, vTPM
  path) works end-to-end.

`internal/helmchart/c8s/values.yaml` gets `secretBroker`, `secretAgent`,
and `luks` blocks. Broker deploys as a mesh component under
`kata.enabled` (its plaintext egress from ratls-mesh must stay inside
the TEE). Broker port defaults to 8443, credential mounts as a file.

`secretAgent.image` and `luks.image` are external-image entries in
`c8sComponents` (new `externalImage: true` flag) — the CLI doesn't
rewrite --image-tag over them (openbao/openbao has its own version
stream; the LUKS image defaults to the c8s image which needs
cryptsetup baked in — the current c8s Dockerfile is debian:12-slim
with `cryptsetup + util-linux + e2fsprogs + xfsprogs + ca-certificates`
for exactly this reason).

Unit-tested throughout — 44 packages, 5.9k LOC added. Highlights:

* internal/webhook: parseSecretsInjection matrix (name validation,
  sorting, opt-in required), parseLUKSVolumes matrix (all fields
  including sort determinism, opt-in required, matching secret-<name>
  required), mutatePod end-to-end (injects the four init containers in
  the correct order + volumes + privileged securityContext on
  luks-open).
* internal/cmds/luksopen: ParseVolumeSpecs (name=dev:secretName:fstype:mode
  form; error path for bad shapes), trimTrailingNewline.
* internal/cmds/luks: generatePassphrase (entropy bounds), KV path
  shape, validateCreate matrix, luksMode helper, full mock openbao
  HTTP round-trip (put / list / show / delete).
* internal/issuer: two new tests exercising the .1.1 embed round-trip
  (SNP report unmarshal via ratls.UnmarshalExtension; server-supplied
  Attestation wins over any client-supplied .1.1 in the CSR — exactly
  one .1.1 extension on the leaf).
* internal/cmds/cds: attest.go regression harness picks up the new
  Attestation field automatically via existing verifier fixtures.
* internal/helmchart: full chart render suite exercises every values
  toggle (secretBroker.enabled / peerVerify / kata combinations,
  luks.enabled, the fail-render validations kind=broker_ratls_under_kata
  and the LUKS admission guards).

Full `go test ./...` green.

Follow-ups (tracked in the decision docs, not blocking):
* Option A step 2 — identity forwarding via ratls-mesh OR out-of-mesh
  broker port, to close the kata-inbound gap.
* Label secret-broker as a mesh peer so outbound from CW pods rides
  the mesh mTLS path.
* `c8s luks` `--driver pvc` (controller for first-bind LUKS format)
  and `--driver csi`.
* Rotation: `c8s luks rotate` via cryptsetup luksAddKey/luksRemoveKey.
* dm-integrity under dm-crypt for the block-device integrity story.

